input: rind@enterprise.bih.harvard.edu (David Rind) writes: >In article <1993Apr22.153000.1@vms.ocom.okstate.edu> > banschbach@vms.ocom.okstate.edu writes: >>poster for being treated by a liscenced physician for a disease that did  >>not exist.
Calling this physician a quack was reprehensible Steve and I  >>see that you and some of the others are doing it here as well.
>Do you believe that any quacks exist?
How about quack diagnoses?
Is >being a "licensed physician" enough to guarantee that someone is not >a quack, or is it just that even if a licensed physician is a quack, >other people should not say so?

Can you give an example of a >commonly diagnosed ailment that you think is a quack diagnosis, >or have we gotten to the point in civilization where we no longer >need to worry about unscrupulous "healers" taking advantage of >people.
>David Rind Sure there are quacks.
There are quacks who do not treat and quacks who treat.
One that refuse to diagnose and ones that diagnose improperly.
There are lucky quacks and unlucky quacks.
Smart quacks and dumb ones.
There are people ahead of their time, with unprobable or unproven theories and rationals.
There are ill-reasoned, absurd, theorists.
Sometimes it is hard to tell who is who.
Reading a book of ancient jokes it seems that doctors called other doctors quacks in Babylon.
Arguments abound when there are not any firm answers.
Plenty of illnesses are not, or can not, be diagnosed or treated.
But I think it is better to argue against the theory, as was originally done with postings on candida a month or so ago.
Stating the facts usually works better than simply asserting an opinion about someone is competency.
And you can not convince everybody.

Sometimes a correct diagnosis takes years for people: they do not run into a doctor who recognizes the disease, they have not developed something recognizable yet, or they have something that no one is going to recognize, because it has not been described yet.
Sometimes they get a cure, sometimes the illness wears out, sometimes they stumble on an improper diagnosis with the right treatment, sometimes they find it is incurable.
There is no profit in a patient accepting a hopeless attitude about an  illness.
Unless it is a rock solid diagnosis of terminal disease it is is more like ly that a person will find a cure if they keep looking.
-Jackie-
